WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.440
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:06.730
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: Welcome
to a very creative afternoon

00:00:06.730 --> 00:00:08.720
and an Authors AtGoogle Talk.

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:09.740
My name is Frederik.

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:13.592
Please join me in welcoming
David and Tom Kelley.

00:00:13.592 --> 00:00:15.802
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:15.802 --> 00:00:20.850
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: They've
just published recently a book,

00:00:20.850 --> 00:00:24.285
"Creative Confidence: Unleashing
the Creative Potential

00:00:24.285 --> 00:00:26.610
Within Us All."

00:00:26.610 --> 00:00:30.080
And I actually had the
pleasure of having lunch

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:31.720
with Tom and David.

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:34.750
And David asked me, I
think the second question,

00:00:34.750 --> 00:00:37.160
so what are we going to do here?

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:39.720
Google is already very creative.

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:44.050
So let us come back to
that question later on.

00:00:44.050 --> 00:00:46.680
So, Tom, you published
various books

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:49.159
around innovation, "The
Art of Innovation,"

00:00:49.159 --> 00:00:51.200
"The Ten Faces of Innovation,"
bestselling books.

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:52.033
TOM KELLEY: Uh, huh.

00:00:52.033 --> 00:00:55.580
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: So what
motivated you to really publish

00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:57.415
this book around
creative confidence now?

00:00:57.415 --> 00:00:58.860
TOM KELLEY: Sure.

00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:01.670
So this book is actually quite
different than my other books.

00:01:01.670 --> 00:01:03.150
It focuses more
on the individual.

00:01:03.150 --> 00:01:06.260
It's more about creativity
per se and stuff like that.

00:01:06.260 --> 00:01:08.915
So it has a business
audience, but it actually

00:01:08.915 --> 00:01:10.274
speaks to a broader audience.

00:01:10.274 --> 00:01:12.690
So we're a "New York Times"
bestseller as of two days ago.

00:01:12.690 --> 00:01:14.273
And it's not in the
business category.

00:01:14.273 --> 00:01:16.770
It's in the advice category,
which is quite different.

00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:18.750
But why'd I write this book?

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:21.090
And really, the answer is,
you know, two chairs away

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:23.820
from me is my brother.

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:26.740
Back in 2007, David was sick.

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:29.520
David had throat cancer.

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:32.790
And they only gave him a
40% chance of survival.

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:36.400
And, wow, in that situation,
you confront a lot of demons,

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:37.614
you know.

00:01:37.614 --> 00:01:39.780
And that was hanging over
our heads for a long time.

00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:42.550
I spent most of the
year with him in '07.

00:01:42.550 --> 00:01:47.250
And after chemo and radiation,
and eventually surgery,

00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:52.980
toward the end of the year,
at least a possibility arose,

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:55.105
became more tangible, that
he was going to survive,

00:01:55.105 --> 00:01:57.740
And, you know, you
can see, he's there.

00:01:57.740 --> 00:02:02.610
That's the answer
six years later,

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:06.540
And so we had talked
about the future all year.

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:09.180
And so late in
2007, then we did.

00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:11.900
We felt like we had permission
to talk about the future.

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:15.260
And so as we did that, we made
two promises to each other.

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:18.310
David and I have worked
together for almost 30 years.

00:02:18.310 --> 00:02:20.810
And the two promises
were, one, that we

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:21.970
would take a trip together.

00:02:21.970 --> 00:02:27.090
Because, oddly, we have never
traveled together as adults.

00:02:27.090 --> 00:02:29.320
Our big trip was in 1967.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:32.525
We drove from Ohio to
California, you know,

00:02:32.525 --> 00:02:34.670
the promised land.

00:02:34.670 --> 00:02:40.600
And so in our work
at IDEO, if one of us

00:02:40.600 --> 00:02:42.592
goes to a meeting
in Grand Rapids

00:02:42.592 --> 00:02:44.800
or wherever, the other one
doesn't have to go, right?

00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:46.133
And so we don't travel together.

00:02:46.133 --> 00:02:48.240
So promise number one is
to do a trip together.

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:53.110
And that became this really
fun trip to Tokyo and Kyoto,

00:02:53.110 --> 00:02:54.432
two places that I really like.

00:02:54.432 --> 00:02:55.390
And, oh, I got to pick.

00:02:55.390 --> 00:02:57.475
So I picked.

00:02:57.475 --> 00:02:59.100
But then, the other
promise was that we

00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:00.170
would do a project together.

00:03:00.170 --> 00:03:01.970
David and I are not
very good at leisure.

00:03:01.970 --> 00:03:06.490
You know, we're couldn't
just hang out for some months

00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:08.480
together or play
golf or I don't know.

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:10.651
Just not in our DNA.

00:03:10.651 --> 00:03:12.400
And so if you want to
spend time together,

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:14.190
you got to think of something
to work on together.

00:03:14.190 --> 00:03:15.700
And so we said
we'd do a project.

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:18.116
And at that time we didn't
know what the project would be.

00:03:18.116 --> 00:03:19.950
But the project became a book.

00:03:19.950 --> 00:03:22.116
It became the book called
"Creative Confidence" that

00:03:22.116 --> 00:03:22.780
is sitting right there.

00:03:22.780 --> 00:03:24.350
DAVID KELLEY: Yeah,
I actually highly

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:26.620
recommend being diagnosed
with a terminal disease.

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:27.120
Just--

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:28.046
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:28.046 --> 00:03:29.920
DAVID KELLEY: --don't
get a terminal disease.

00:03:29.920 --> 00:03:32.660
But if you could fake
yourself into really believing

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:34.870
that for a while, it's
kind of cathartic.

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:36.320
It'll straighten you right up.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:38.598
You'll do all kinds
of different things.

00:03:38.598 --> 00:03:40.380
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:40.380 --> 00:03:42.380
FREDERIK G. PFERDT:
Speaking of different things

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:44.720
you did in your life,
David, you founded

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:47.800
a very successful
company called IDEO.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:50.850
You also started an educational
institution called the Stanford

00:03:50.850 --> 00:03:53.040
d.school.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:56.995
So you also started a
revolution around innovation

00:03:56.995 --> 00:04:00.140
and innovators in general
and using design thinking

00:04:00.140 --> 00:04:02.805
as a framework to really
push that forward.

00:04:02.805 --> 00:04:04.800
Can you speak a
little bit about what

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:07.911
you have learned
throughout the years,

00:04:07.911 --> 00:04:10.160
about innovation in general
but also about innovators?

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:11.140
DAVID KELLEY: Yeah.

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:15.436
Well, you know, I
mean, we think of IDEO

00:04:15.436 --> 00:04:17.769
as a successful company, you
know, as this little thing.

00:04:17.769 --> 00:04:21.100
When you come here, and it
would fit in one cafeteria,

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:23.130
it doesn't feel that big a deal.

00:04:31.630 --> 00:04:32.770
There's a couple things.

00:04:32.770 --> 00:04:35.420
So one, I'm really
proud of IDEO.

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:37.380
You know, you get a
bunch of designers

00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:40.390
together and then give them a
really difficult problem-- you

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:44.370
know, fix the educational
system in Peru,

00:04:44.370 --> 00:04:48.590
or improve the experience of
checking into the Mayo Clinic,

00:04:48.590 --> 00:04:52.660
or whatever-- and they come
up with really wonderful,

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:55.620
new to the world,
viable solutions.

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:57.480
And that feels really good.

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:01.750
And at the d.school--
d.school's successful

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:03.180
beyond my wildest
dreams-- and you

00:05:03.180 --> 00:05:07.180
see people flip from
thinking of themselves

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:09.660
as not creative to thinking
of themselves as creative.

00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:12.110
And it impacts
their entire life,

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:16.460
the number of people
that kind of come to me

00:05:16.460 --> 00:05:19.205
and say, this thing's changed
my life, as an educator,

00:05:19.205 --> 00:05:23.870
it feels great, especially
since for the first kind of 20

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:26.890
years of my academic career,
I was the design guy.

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:30.271
So when somebody important
in the university

00:05:30.271 --> 00:05:31.770
came to see me,
they wanted to know,

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:35.835
where did you get those shoes,
or where I get cool glasses,

00:05:35.835 --> 00:05:36.650
you know?

00:05:36.650 --> 00:05:40.950
Now, they're coming
with strategic questions

00:05:40.950 --> 00:05:43.310
about what's the future
of higher education,

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:44.330
and can we work on that?

00:05:44.330 --> 00:05:48.660
So I'm just saying it surprised
me and it's really exciting.

00:05:51.730 --> 00:05:53.280
We could go on
and on about that.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:55.860
But if you just want to think
about the highlights of what

00:05:55.860 --> 00:06:01.140
we found, the first
thing is that being

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:04.340
human-centered results
in new innovation.

00:06:04.340 --> 00:06:07.800
So if you think that there's
lots of companies and people

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:11.070
working on coming up
with new business ideas

00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:15.350
and then trying to understand
how people might accept them.

00:06:15.350 --> 00:06:18.570
And then, there's lots of people
coming up with technology ideas

00:06:18.570 --> 00:06:22.400
and trying to figure out how
the business side of that

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:24.450
might work and how
people might accept that.

00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:28.010
And we found that, for
us, for design types,

00:06:28.010 --> 00:06:31.520
the best approach is to
come in from the human side,

00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:36.180
like what do people value,
what's meaningful for people,

00:06:36.180 --> 00:06:38.570
and then go out and try to
find technologies and business

00:06:38.570 --> 00:06:39.840
solutions to those problems.

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:44.780
So that seems to be, for
us, the number one thing.

00:06:44.780 --> 00:06:52.670
This empathy for people is the
best way to lead to innovation.

00:06:52.670 --> 00:06:55.010
And the other thing
is that this is

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:56.267
a team sport, this innovation.

00:06:56.267 --> 00:06:57.600
I mean, there's the lone genius.

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:00.500
I mean, if you've got Leonardo
da Vinci on your team,

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:01.420
you're set, you know.

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:01.920
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:05.270
DAVID KELLEY: But if
you don't, then it's

00:07:05.270 --> 00:07:08.520
really important to have
a team that's very diverse

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:10.310
and that they work together.

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:11.910
They have had
different experiences.

00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:13.576
And they have different
points of views.

00:07:13.576 --> 00:07:16.430
And then, if you can get them
to work together and build on

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:19.904
each other's ideas rather
than just kind of show

00:07:19.904 --> 00:07:21.320
how smart you are
by saying what's

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:22.630
wrong with the
other person's idea,

00:07:22.630 --> 00:07:23.900
if you can get to build on them.

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:25.340
And what happened
at the d.school,

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:27.550
I believe-- lots of things
happened at the d.school--

00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:29.422
but the thing I
believe is that we'd

00:07:29.422 --> 00:07:31.130
been trying to do
multidisciplinary stuff

00:07:31.130 --> 00:07:33.297
at the university for a
long time but, you may know,

00:07:33.297 --> 00:07:35.921
if you've been in a university,
that it's the opposite of that.

00:07:35.921 --> 00:07:36.840
It's in deep silos.

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:38.399
And people are
winning Nobel Prizes.

00:07:38.399 --> 00:07:40.440
And I would hope that they
would keep doing that.

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:42.490
I'm not trying to talk
people out of going deep.

00:07:42.490 --> 00:07:43.739
I think that's very important.

00:07:43.739 --> 00:07:49.070
But we kind of miss things
in between these deep silos

00:07:49.070 --> 00:07:49.710
of knowledge.

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:54.960
And so what we found is
that by having people

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:58.950
from different disciplines, you
get to these kind of big ideas

00:07:58.950 --> 00:08:02.850
that are between
disciplines by using methods

00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:06.321
like design thinking and
having these diverse teams that

00:08:06.321 --> 00:08:07.320
can build on each other.

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:11.032
So that's the basic
thing that's happened.

00:08:11.032 --> 00:08:12.990
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: You
both write in your book

00:08:12.990 --> 00:08:16.400
that you want to make
the world a better place

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:20.912
through embracing creative
confidence in our lives.

00:08:20.912 --> 00:08:23.020
At Google, we have
a similar mission

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:26.740
on making the world a better
place through technology.

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:29.165
So where do you
see the parallels

00:08:29.165 --> 00:08:32.434
in what you're trying
to achieve and what

00:08:32.434 --> 00:08:34.100
we're trying to achieve
with technology.

00:08:34.100 --> 00:08:34.808
TOM KELLEY: Sure.

00:08:34.808 --> 00:08:37.789
I mean, those two are not in
conflict in any way, right?

00:08:37.789 --> 00:08:43.070
What we're seeing is this
trend, this kind of maker trend,

00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:45.880
that we've experienced both
in our teams and in the world

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:50.200
at large, in which
new technologies put

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:52.785
creative tools in
everybody's hands.

00:08:52.785 --> 00:08:55.910
You know, there's that old line
about, in the 20th century,

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:56.660
kids watch TV.

00:08:56.660 --> 00:08:58.077
In the 21st century,
kids make TV.

00:08:58.077 --> 00:08:59.618
I think they're
talking about YouTube

00:08:59.618 --> 00:09:00.860
when they say that, right?

00:09:00.860 --> 00:09:04.620
And so I think the
two go hand in hand.

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:06.110
I mean, we just
maybe approach it

00:09:06.110 --> 00:09:07.850
from a slightly
different direction.

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:11.850
But one of the things that
we've latched on to early on

00:09:11.850 --> 00:09:14.850
is a year or two ago there
was an Adobe study called

00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:17.960
"State of Create,"
in which they, you

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:19.980
know, with an interest
not unlike yours--

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:24.200
they want to use technology
to help people in their focus

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:26.820
on creativity-- and so they
ask 5,000 people in five

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:29.220
different countries
about their beliefs

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:31.390
surrounding creativity--
one about the link

00:09:31.390 --> 00:09:33.500
between creativity and
economic development.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:35.910
And 80% of people
said, unlocking

00:09:35.910 --> 00:09:38.920
creativity is critical to
economic development, which

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:40.000
we thought was great.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.970
But really interesting was
the follow-on question.

00:09:42.970 --> 00:09:45.000
And they said,
well, how about you?

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:46.970
How about you as an individual?

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:50.690
Do you have a chance to live
up to your creative potential?

00:09:50.690 --> 00:09:52.190
In other words, do
you have a chance

00:09:52.190 --> 00:09:53.720
to bring your
whole self to work?

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:58.820
And across the world, only 25%
of the people said yes to that.

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:00.840
And so we think
it's a worthy goal.

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:04.650
I mean, it's a worthy
question, for us and for you,

00:10:04.650 --> 00:10:07.495
of how might we
unlock the creativity

00:10:07.495 --> 00:10:10.150
of the other 75%, right?

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:12.630
And so you might
approach that question

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:15.260
from a slightly different
direction than us.

00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:17.780
But I think we're
both quite interested

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:20.490
in how to change the
world in that way.

00:10:20.490 --> 00:10:22.950
DAVID KELLY: You just
have 42,000 people on it.

00:10:22.950 --> 00:10:23.860
We have five.

00:10:23.860 --> 00:10:24.954
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:24.954 --> 00:10:26.370
FREDERIK G. PFERDT:
So coming back

00:10:26.370 --> 00:10:30.060
to that question, so how
would you actually recommend

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:31.900
organizations going
about unlocking

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:34.959
the potential of creative
people in their organizations?

00:10:34.959 --> 00:10:35.750
DAVID KELLEY: Yeah.

00:10:35.750 --> 00:10:38.120
I'm not sure this applies
to Google, as I said before,

00:10:38.120 --> 00:10:41.650
but what we find is that
you have to have support

00:10:41.650 --> 00:10:45.290
from the top of the company
that the experiments are allowed

00:10:45.290 --> 00:10:45.790
to happen.

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:48.350
But it's all really
about small experiments.

00:10:48.350 --> 00:10:51.010
It's all about starting a
bunch of little brush fires

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:52.800
in different places
in the company

00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:54.436
and hoping that
they kind of, you

00:10:54.436 --> 00:10:57.060
know, catch on
and grow together.

00:10:57.060 --> 00:11:01.440
So we, in all of our
exec eds at the d.school,

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:07.790
from the minute the people
come to go through our program

00:11:07.790 --> 00:11:09.610
and learn our
methods and stuff, we

00:11:09.610 --> 00:11:11.900
focus on what are they going
to do when they get back?

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:15.450
I mean, how do you
implement when you get back,

00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:18.830
and how are you going to
protect these ideas and stuff?

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:21.350
Because one of the
things, and early on,

00:11:21.350 --> 00:11:24.097
is that people would have
this cathartic experience.

00:11:24.097 --> 00:11:24.930
Then they'd go back.

00:11:24.930 --> 00:11:28.240
And the mass of the place,
the habit of the place

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:30.550
they were going to,
was just too extreme

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:32.000
for them to catch hold, right?

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.990
And so we spend a
lot of time trying

00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:39.340
to understand how
you kind of come up

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:43.000
with these ideas in a
way that can be accepted

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:44.797
by the rest of the organization.

00:11:44.797 --> 00:11:45.631
TOM KELLEY: Yeah.

00:11:45.631 --> 00:11:48.750
You know, in cultures there's
a really important moment we've

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:49.510
discovered.

00:11:49.510 --> 00:11:52.360
And I personally have worked
with 1,500 clients, and David,

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:53.910
I'm sure, a lot more.

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:55.770
And there's a really
important moment

00:11:55.770 --> 00:12:01.370
in which a not yet perfect
idea gets put on the table.

00:12:01.370 --> 00:12:04.376
And people look
really closely to see

00:12:04.376 --> 00:12:07.716
how do leaders
especially react to that.

00:12:07.716 --> 00:12:09.590
You know, you've probably
heard those stories

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:12.310
about the tyrant boss who, you
bring in the unfinished thing,

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:14.290
and they say, how
would our organization

00:12:14.290 --> 00:12:16.840
be worse if you weren't
here tomorrow, you know,

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:19.380
that kind of, like,
get out of my office,

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:21.380
because you haven't thought
through every detail

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:22.930
of this idea yet.

00:12:22.930 --> 00:12:25.850
But in great cultures,
in creative cultures,

00:12:25.850 --> 00:12:29.640
the first instinct is
to build on the idea.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:32.320
There's a skill
we call squinting,

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:34.600
in which you ignore
the surface details

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:36.540
and you look at the
shape of the idea

00:12:36.540 --> 00:12:38.720
and try to figure out how
could you make it better.

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:42.330
And if the leaders of an
organization are squinters,

00:12:42.330 --> 00:12:43.830
you know, are the
kind of people who

00:12:43.830 --> 00:12:46.100
look past the
surface details, what

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:51.447
we found is, there's a better
idea flow within the company.

00:12:51.447 --> 00:12:53.780
More ideas come up, because
you don't have to self-edit.

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:55.863
You don't have to wait
until your idea is perfect.

00:12:55.863 --> 00:12:58.320
You bring it out in
its embryonic form

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:00.980
and say, well, I'm thinking
about this, because you're

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:04.130
allowed to kind of think
out loud about things.

00:13:04.130 --> 00:13:07.540
You know, here in the Valley,
ask any venture capitalist,

00:13:07.540 --> 00:13:10.400
and they will tell you that
all other things equal,

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:12.250
the VC firm with
the better deal flow

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:15.500
wins, right, because they're
picking from 1,000 instead

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:18.570
of picking from
five possibilities.

00:13:18.570 --> 00:13:21.650
And so we think it's true
with companies with idea flow.

00:13:21.650 --> 00:13:24.150
If you're the kind of company--
and I know that in many ways

00:13:24.150 --> 00:13:27.180
you are-- if you're the kind
of company in which ideas get

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:30.200
circulated all of the time--
and many fall by the wayside,

00:13:30.200 --> 00:13:34.780
because they're not yet perfect
or because they don't pan out--

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:40.060
you still have this rich
culture of ideas to choose from.

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:42.490
What we found is that those
are the companies that

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:45.446
succeed and sustain
in the long run.

00:13:45.446 --> 00:13:46.820
FREDERIK G. PFERDT:
So let's move

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:48.986
from an organizational level
to an individual level.

00:13:48.986 --> 00:13:50.984
I think that's very interesting.

00:13:50.984 --> 00:13:52.400
So what prevents,
actually, people

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:54.066
for having those
creative breakthroughs?

00:13:54.066 --> 00:13:57.692
So is there a routine,
especially like if, maybe, you

00:13:57.692 --> 00:13:59.900
have a personal routine you
want to share about David

00:13:59.900 --> 00:14:01.316
or David wants to
share about Tom,

00:14:01.316 --> 00:14:05.890
like how you actually
train the creative muscle,

00:14:05.890 --> 00:14:07.350
if that's even possible.

00:14:07.350 --> 00:14:09.744
So some people do meditation,
and they would go work out.

00:14:09.744 --> 00:14:10.660
So what are you doing?

00:14:10.660 --> 00:14:13.360
DAVID KELLEY: Well, again--
I don't know about Google

00:14:13.360 --> 00:14:15.110
and that it makes sense
now about Google--

00:14:15.110 --> 00:14:19.625
but what's really going
on in these people that

00:14:19.625 --> 00:14:21.507
aren't confident in
their creative ability

00:14:21.507 --> 00:14:23.590
is something happened to
them when they were kids,

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:27.160
and they opted out of thinking
of themselves as creative.

00:14:27.160 --> 00:14:29.619
They think of themselves only
as analytical, which is fine.

00:14:29.619 --> 00:14:31.160
We're not saying
don't be analytical.

00:14:31.160 --> 00:14:33.040
We're saying be
creative, as well.

00:14:33.040 --> 00:14:36.190
And so what happens
is they develop

00:14:36.190 --> 00:14:40.620
this fear of kind
of owning an idea.

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:43.260
Like you don't want to
be the person who came up

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:47.920
with that idea, because then
as it goes through the company,

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:51.060
and if it doesn't work, then
you are labeled with that idea.

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:54.080
So it's that kind of
fear of being judged.

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:58.950
And so, I mean,
whatever it is-- I mean,

00:14:58.950 --> 00:15:01.620
I don't understand Google's
culture-- but whatever it is,

00:15:01.620 --> 00:15:05.030
there's fears that
can be alleviated

00:15:05.030 --> 00:15:09.000
by this process we
call guided mastery.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:10.830
And some of you may
have seen my TED Talk.

00:15:10.830 --> 00:15:13.540
I talked about this
guy that I really

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:15.800
kind of got to
enjoy at Stanford.

00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:17.590
His name is Albert Bandura.

00:15:17.590 --> 00:15:20.260
If you're a psychology major,
you know who Albert Bandura is.

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:24.790
He's like the most cited
psychologist in the world,

00:15:24.790 --> 00:15:26.790
living.

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:30.740
Freud probably has more
citations somewhere.

00:15:30.740 --> 00:15:34.740
And when I met
him, he was talking

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:37.650
about this kind
of curing phobias.

00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:40.160
Now, lots of people
that we run into

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:42.100
have this fear of being judged.

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:44.150
And it turns out, it's
the same deal as far as

00:15:44.150 --> 00:15:46.950
how you get around
it, how you change

00:15:46.950 --> 00:15:49.160
the way you think of
that, of yourself.

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:52.600
And so he was curing
snakes and spiders

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:54.810
phobias and stuff like that.

00:15:54.810 --> 00:15:57.450
And the way he did it, in this
thing called guided mastery,

00:15:57.450 --> 00:15:59.770
is he takes people through
a series of small steps,

00:15:59.770 --> 00:16:00.680
you know, baby steps.

00:16:00.680 --> 00:16:03.030
And each one, they're
successful at it.

00:16:03.030 --> 00:16:05.560
So you're looking at the
snake through the mirror.

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:08.550
And then 15 steps
later, you're standing

00:16:08.550 --> 00:16:11.960
at the door, your
hand being held.

00:16:11.960 --> 00:16:13.780
Then you get to
a welder's glove.

00:16:13.780 --> 00:16:15.300
And eventually, you
touch the snake.

00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:20.255
But there's a guy who's got a
near 100% cure rate of people

00:16:20.255 --> 00:16:21.380
with these kind of phobias.

00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:23.780
And they've had these
phobias their whole lives,

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:26.120
and they're not going
outside or going on a hike

00:16:26.120 --> 00:16:27.690
because there might
be a snake there.

00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:29.830
And he can cure them
through this guided mastery.

00:16:29.830 --> 00:16:32.420
So what we feel, when you
talk about the individual,

00:16:32.420 --> 00:16:35.150
we know, at the d.school
and IDEO, anyplace,

00:16:35.150 --> 00:16:40.650
if we take people who have
this fear of being judged

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:43.500
or of failing or whatever
in the workplace,

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:46.450
and we can take them through
a series of successes--

00:16:46.450 --> 00:16:48.789
we give them a small
project just like when

00:16:48.789 --> 00:16:49.830
you were at the d.school.

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:53.160
You know, we have
a small project

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:55.290
that you can be
somewhat successful at.

00:16:55.290 --> 00:16:58.240
And then we increase the
complexity and the scope

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:00.370
and the team size and
all of that stuff.

00:17:00.370 --> 00:17:03.880
And it's not that long,
after a few projects,

00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:07.170
that you're thinking, oh, my,
god, I am a creative person.

00:17:07.170 --> 00:17:11.280
So for the book, we interviewed
100 people, most of them

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:13.380
from the d.school,
and just talking

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:16.290
about their extraordinary
transformation

00:17:16.290 --> 00:17:20.089
by gaining this feeling in
their bodies of being creative.

00:17:20.089 --> 00:17:25.500
And so it's pretty
amazing to watch

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:28.270
how this can be transformative
to the individual.

00:17:30.920 --> 00:17:33.010
FREDERIK G. PFERDT:
You spoke a little bit

00:17:33.010 --> 00:17:37.880
about this beginner's
mind or child's mind,

00:17:37.880 --> 00:17:42.630
and you quoted, I
think, a lot of times,

00:17:42.630 --> 00:17:46.580
that you should really embrace
that in everything you're

00:17:46.580 --> 00:17:47.100
doing.

00:17:47.100 --> 00:17:52.300
So what would you actually
recommend for parents then?

00:17:52.300 --> 00:17:54.320
Because I saw that in
your book, you also

00:17:54.320 --> 00:17:56.204
dedicate your book
to your parents.

00:17:56.204 --> 00:17:58.370
What would you recommend--
that's the first question

00:17:58.370 --> 00:18:02.610
for you-- for parents, what
they should do with their kids?

00:18:02.610 --> 00:18:05.080
But secondly, how
did your parents

00:18:05.080 --> 00:18:08.080
influence you
throughout your lives?

00:18:08.080 --> 00:18:10.690
TOM KELLEY: Sure.

00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:12.650
You know, this
parenting thing is hard,

00:18:12.650 --> 00:18:14.210
as you've probably noticed.

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:16.220
Those kids don't come
with instruction sets.

00:18:16.220 --> 00:18:18.470
It's sometimes hard
to know, is this

00:18:18.470 --> 00:18:19.720
where I'm supposed to be firm?

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:22.220
Is this where I'm supposed to
be laissez-faire, or whatever?

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:24.155
But just think
about our parents.

00:18:24.155 --> 00:18:28.260
It wasn't that they were
artists or something.

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:31.750
It wasn't that they got out
the finger paints with us

00:18:31.750 --> 00:18:32.660
every day.

00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:35.850
It was that they give us a
lot of space to do things,

00:18:35.850 --> 00:18:37.940
that they weren't
quick to judge us

00:18:37.940 --> 00:18:40.942
or to kind of reign us in
when we got a little creative.

00:18:40.942 --> 00:18:42.650
You know, David and
I took a lot of stuff

00:18:42.650 --> 00:18:45.510
apart as kids, including
the family piano.

00:18:45.510 --> 00:18:48.159
And many of those things
never went back together.

00:18:48.159 --> 00:18:49.700
A piano, once you
take it apart, it's

00:18:49.700 --> 00:18:50.824
actually kind of beautiful.

00:18:50.824 --> 00:18:52.970
Those 88 hammers, David's
got those up on his wall.

00:18:52.970 --> 00:18:55.040
But nobody ever played
that piano afterwards.

00:18:55.040 --> 00:18:57.050
And the parents
never complained.

00:18:57.050 --> 00:19:00.040
And so I think it's
just kind of permission

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:03.090
to misbehave a little bit,
permission to be creative.

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:06.680
And you have this sort
of nurturing environment

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:09.200
that says, and it's still
going to be OK, right?

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:11.540
And so that's really what
our parents did for us.

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:14.500
And that's what I've
tried to do for my kids.

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:18.250
DAVID KELLEY: It could be
called benign neglect, right?

00:19:18.250 --> 00:19:21.180
So we got away with it.

00:19:21.180 --> 00:19:23.020
The one I remember
the most, or that I've

00:19:23.020 --> 00:19:26.770
been told the most it
was hardest to take, was,

00:19:26.770 --> 00:19:27.670
so, I was 12.

00:19:27.670 --> 00:19:30.606
I got a brand new
red Schwinn bicycle.

00:19:30.606 --> 00:19:32.410
You can imagine,
that's a big gift.

00:19:32.410 --> 00:19:35.800
We're, you know, relatively
not that well-heeled a family.

00:19:35.800 --> 00:19:37.520
And so a Schwinn
bike was a big deal.

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:40.630
And somehow the next day I
took it out and sandblasted it

00:19:40.630 --> 00:19:43.446
and painted it
fluorescent green.

00:19:43.446 --> 00:19:45.320
And so, I can imagine,
that was a little hard

00:19:45.320 --> 00:19:47.007
to look the other way.

00:19:47.007 --> 00:19:49.340
TOM KELLEY: Well, speaking
of fluorescent green, so, OK,

00:19:49.340 --> 00:19:50.334
that was David's bike.

00:19:50.334 --> 00:19:52.500
And so it's kind of his to
do whatever he wanted to.

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:55.130
But he came home from college--
he went to Carnegie Mellon

00:19:55.130 --> 00:19:57.463
as an undergrad-- and he came
home from college freshman

00:19:57.463 --> 00:20:00.440
year, and he got four
shades of green paint,

00:20:00.440 --> 00:20:03.440
including fluorescent
green, and painted a stripe,

00:20:03.440 --> 00:20:06.340
like four feet high
and 40 feet long,

00:20:06.340 --> 00:20:08.970
against the back
wall of the house.

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:12.020
And you can imagine a parent
in a small town in Ohio

00:20:12.020 --> 00:20:13.770
being not sure
about that, right?

00:20:13.770 --> 00:20:16.750
But that green stripe's still
there all these years later.

00:20:16.750 --> 00:20:18.650
DAVID KELLEY: Yeah,
you're mostly too young.

00:20:18.650 --> 00:20:21.664
But this was the era of
super graphics, right?

00:20:21.664 --> 00:20:24.472
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: So
what changed about David?

00:20:24.472 --> 00:20:25.945
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:25.945 --> 00:20:28.077
TOM KELLEY: You can Google that.

00:20:28.077 --> 00:20:29.160
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: Great.

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:31.970
What changed about David
over the years, then?

00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:33.390
You spoke about when he was 12.

00:20:33.390 --> 00:20:35.990
But what's really now when
you say, oh, David, that's

00:20:35.990 --> 00:20:38.572
really why you're
childlike, not childish?

00:20:38.572 --> 00:20:39.280
TOM KELLEY: Sure.

00:20:39.280 --> 00:20:41.844
So there's that great
quote from Picasso.

00:20:41.844 --> 00:20:43.260
He says, every
child is an artist,

00:20:43.260 --> 00:20:47.340
and the challenge is to remain
an artist after you grow up.

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:50.010
So David and I were
quite different as kids.

00:20:50.010 --> 00:20:54.520
And the thing about David
is he had indication,

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:57.110
there were tells even
as a small child,

00:20:57.110 --> 00:20:58.590
that he was going
to be creative,

00:20:58.590 --> 00:21:02.950
that he was going to become a
designer one day or something,

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:04.710
whereas I was the opposite.

00:21:04.710 --> 00:21:06.780
You couldn't have
spotted it in me.

00:21:06.780 --> 00:21:09.423
And so I think that--
for a lot of you,

00:21:09.423 --> 00:21:12.680
you might have fit David's
pattern more as kids--

00:21:12.680 --> 00:21:15.560
but the fact that I could
cross over that line,

00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:19.160
I think is good news for lots
of people out in the business

00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:20.700
community and beyond.

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:23.840
Because I wanted to be a
lawyer, for God's sake.

00:21:23.840 --> 00:21:24.810
What was I thinking?

00:21:24.810 --> 00:21:26.140
I'm not sure.

00:21:26.140 --> 00:21:28.380
I got the GMAT,
abandoned that, but got

00:21:28.380 --> 00:21:30.840
an MBA, worked for
an accounting firm,

00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:33.600
worked five years doing
spreadsheets-- first

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:37.960
by hand, because we didn't have
those computer things, and then

00:21:37.960 --> 00:21:42.760
on the early laptop
machines-- and so

00:21:42.760 --> 00:21:46.760
at age 35, no
indication, right, that I

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:49.410
was going to have a chance
to have a creative life.

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:50.460
And so this is good news.

00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:52.450
Because you can decide today.

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:54.550
You can change later in life.

00:21:54.550 --> 00:21:56.790
And so I just basically
immersed myself

00:21:56.790 --> 00:22:00.120
in the creative
environment at IDEO

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:03.340
and gained creative
confidence in that process.

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:05.810
And so, you know, yeah, you
could spot the stuff in David,

00:22:05.810 --> 00:22:11.115
but, yeah, hard to tell
in some of the rest of us.

00:22:11.115 --> 00:22:14.460
FREDERIK G. PFERDT:
So two more questions.

00:22:14.460 --> 00:22:17.350
And then, I want to open
it up for the Googlers

00:22:17.350 --> 00:22:20.230
to ask questions to you.

00:22:20.230 --> 00:22:25.520
The first one is, when you
think about what's next--

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:27.120
so in the next
five to 10 years--

00:22:27.120 --> 00:22:29.690
I think that's a time
frame we as Googlers think,

00:22:29.690 --> 00:22:32.500
like it's way in the
future, but it's still

00:22:32.500 --> 00:22:35.130
something you can
somehow guess what's

00:22:35.130 --> 00:22:37.540
going on-- so what
are your plans?

00:22:37.540 --> 00:22:39.910
You started a
successful company.

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:44.590
You started a successful
educational institution.

00:22:44.590 --> 00:22:47.590
You wrote various books
really successfully.

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:49.035
So what's next?

00:22:49.035 --> 00:22:52.020
TOM KELLEY: You know, I bet
David's got his own answer.

00:22:52.020 --> 00:22:56.230
But for me, this book
is out, and it's done,

00:22:56.230 --> 00:22:57.540
and books are so hard.

00:22:57.540 --> 00:23:00.060
I'm not sure I'm
doing another one.

00:23:00.060 --> 00:23:05.370
So the idea is out
in the world now.

00:23:05.370 --> 00:23:08.600
But I feel like it's got a
pretty long run, this idea

00:23:08.600 --> 00:23:11.969
of creative confidence,
that dealing with the 75%.

00:23:11.969 --> 00:23:13.635
And so I've been
working on innovations,

00:23:13.635 --> 00:23:17.100
you know, the
products, the services,

00:23:17.100 --> 00:23:19.770
the digital experiences
for 30 years.

00:23:19.770 --> 00:23:21.700
And I was thinking,
the next decade

00:23:21.700 --> 00:23:26.460
or so, that I would focus
more, or at least as much,

00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:29.620
on innovators, on inspiring
individuals-- especially

00:23:29.620 --> 00:23:31.120
early in their
careers, because they

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:34.435
have so much promise
coming up-- to get

00:23:34.435 --> 00:23:36.060
in touch with their
creative confidence

00:23:36.060 --> 00:23:38.910
so they can make a bigger
impact on the world

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:41.090
and have more fun at work.

00:23:41.090 --> 00:23:42.700
You know, we did
those 100 interviews.

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:45.790
And it is so much fun to
be around those people who

00:23:45.790 --> 00:23:47.530
