00:25:59.990 --> 00:26:02.260
about what makes
something really

00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:05.984
scale, especially in K-12.

00:26:05.984 --> 00:26:08.150
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: So
Googlers in general, I think,

00:26:08.150 --> 00:26:09.630
are really passionate
about working

00:26:09.630 --> 00:26:11.820
on big, audacious goals.

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:16.910
So what would be one big,
audacious goal or problem

00:26:16.910 --> 00:26:20.690
for you which a lot of people
should actually work on

00:26:20.690 --> 00:26:22.630
in the next three or four years?

00:26:22.630 --> 00:26:25.490
DAVID KELLEY: Well, I
don't know if you know.

00:26:25.490 --> 00:26:27.590
I've been going to TED
for 20 years or so.

00:26:27.590 --> 00:26:31.735
And the biggest, the most
watched TED Talk is Ken

00:26:31.735 --> 00:26:33.350
Robinson's.

00:26:33.350 --> 00:26:39.160
And in that, he said that
he thought in schools,

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:42.530
creativity was as
important as literacy.

00:26:42.530 --> 00:26:44.850
And we're a long way
from believing that.

00:26:44.850 --> 00:26:52.150
But I really think that through
technology and through doing

00:26:52.150 --> 00:26:55.370
things like project-based
learning and stuff,

00:26:55.370 --> 00:26:57.200
I think that's the
audacious goal.

00:27:01.199 --> 00:27:02.740
I mean, there's
plenty of other ones.

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:08.070
But from my perspective,
or from our perspective,

00:27:08.070 --> 00:27:09.860
and the same thing at
Stanford, how do you

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:13.840
get creative confidence into as
many kids as you possibly can?

00:27:13.840 --> 00:27:17.450
Because when we do
succeed, you just

00:27:17.450 --> 00:27:19.510
see how it's transformative.

00:27:19.510 --> 00:27:22.850
TOM KELLY: Yeah, and for
me I would say the big goal

00:27:22.850 --> 00:27:24.890
would be cracking the
code on behavior change.

00:27:24.890 --> 00:27:27.749
You know, so much of what we
do, all of our social innovation

00:27:27.749 --> 00:27:29.790
work, and even our work
in health care and things

00:27:29.790 --> 00:27:32.000
like that, we're trying
to change behavior

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.180
of the constituents
that matter to us.

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:35.842
They're not always
customers, even.

00:27:35.842 --> 00:27:36.800
And that's really hard.

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:38.500
People cling to
their old patterns

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:42.430
even when their old patterns
aren't the best for them.

00:27:42.430 --> 00:27:44.600
And so, for example,
I did a work

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:46.320
with the water in
developing countries.

00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:48.430
We're in India
trying to get people

00:27:48.430 --> 00:27:50.890
to drink the safe water,
the filtered water,

00:27:50.890 --> 00:27:53.620
the water that won't
make them sick.

00:27:53.620 --> 00:27:57.200
But they've been drinking that
other water for generations.

00:27:57.200 --> 00:28:01.610
And so the old way to do that,
the attempted behavior change

00:28:01.610 --> 00:28:04.790
approach to that, is you send a
social worker into the village,

00:28:04.790 --> 00:28:06.775
and they talk about the
germ theory of disease,

00:28:06.775 --> 00:28:08.520
you know, fascinating
stuff, right?

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:11.080
And they're explaining
why you shouldn't really

00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:13.270
drink that water from the
well, at least untreated.

00:28:13.270 --> 00:28:16.090
You should get this other
water, which is not free, right?

00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:18.180
Now, we're talking
about families

00:28:18.180 --> 00:28:22.000
for whom any new expense means
trading off something else.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.400
They're living very
close to the Earth.

00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:28.760
And so they'll be there, really,
with their best interests

00:28:28.760 --> 00:28:31.720
at heart, trying to
convince this community

00:28:31.720 --> 00:28:33.450
to go for the safe water.

00:28:33.450 --> 00:28:35.130
And then, someone
will raise their hand.

00:28:35.130 --> 00:28:36.796
And apparently it
happens a fair amount.

00:28:36.796 --> 00:28:39.100
Someone will raise their
hand and says something like,

00:28:39.100 --> 00:28:44.180
well, you know, my mother
gave me water from that well.

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:46.650
You're not saying my
mom is wrong, are you?

00:28:46.650 --> 00:28:49.482
And if you're that social worker
in that little village in India

00:28:49.482 --> 00:28:50.940
and that question
comes up, I would

00:28:50.940 --> 00:28:53.040
urge you to just
leave immediately.

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:55.300
There is no beating
that question.

00:28:55.300 --> 00:28:56.825
You're not going
to change behavior

00:28:56.825 --> 00:29:00.072
in that village that day.

00:29:00.072 --> 00:29:01.530
Because we're very
conscious, we're

00:29:01.530 --> 00:29:02.988
hiring behavioral
economists, we're

00:29:02.988 --> 00:29:05.550
very interested in this
behavior change, what

00:29:05.550 --> 00:29:08.722
we do is we show up in the
village with our own generator,

00:29:08.722 --> 00:29:10.430
because you can't
trust the power supply,

00:29:10.430 --> 00:29:14.170
and a projector and a white
sheet that becomes our screen.

00:29:14.170 --> 00:29:15.920
And during the day,
we hand out pamphlets.

00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:18.480
And then we start with singing
and dancing, because you know,

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:20.580
if you advertise germ
theory of disease,

00:29:20.580 --> 00:29:22.210
not everybody shows up, right?

00:29:22.210 --> 00:29:25.020
And so singing and
dancing, we've got a crowd.

00:29:25.020 --> 00:29:26.896
And then, with the crowd
assembled-- and it's

00:29:26.896 --> 00:29:28.895
pretty much the whole
village, because what else

00:29:28.895 --> 00:29:30.320
is going on that
night, right, you

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:32.830
know, they're not watching
reruns of anything,

00:29:32.830 --> 00:29:35.665
because there's no
TVs, right, and so we

00:29:35.665 --> 00:29:37.790
got the attention of the
whole village-- we hook up

00:29:37.790 --> 00:29:40.790
a microscope to that projector.

00:29:40.790 --> 00:29:43.630
And we show them a
drop of the water

00:29:43.630 --> 00:29:46.157
they've been drinking
for generations.

00:29:46.157 --> 00:29:47.740
And we don't have
to check in advance.

00:29:47.740 --> 00:29:49.470
It is alive with small animals.

00:29:49.470 --> 00:29:56.050
It is really scary to see
your filthy water in that way.

00:29:56.050 --> 00:29:58.780
And then, we go to some local
supplier of the safe water,

00:29:58.780 --> 00:30:00.290
and we put a drop of that on it.

00:30:00.290 --> 00:30:01.390
And it's not always
perfect, by the way.

00:30:01.390 --> 00:30:03.098
But it's always way,
way better than this

00:30:03.098 --> 00:30:05.460
really scary looking
water with the animals

00:30:05.460 --> 00:30:07.304
in it, very small animals.

00:30:07.304 --> 00:30:08.845
And then we ask a
different question.

00:30:08.845 --> 00:30:12.300
And the behavioral economists
call this choice architecture,

00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:15.540
which is the ability to
frame the question in a way

00:30:15.540 --> 00:30:17.815
that people make answers
that are true to their belief

00:30:17.815 --> 00:30:18.315
system.

00:30:18.315 --> 00:30:22.130
And so now they've
seen the unsafe water.

00:30:22.130 --> 00:30:24.030
They've seen the safe water.

00:30:24.030 --> 00:30:26.560
And we say, never mind your mom.

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:27.940
Your mom did the best she could.

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:29.570
We address them as parents.

00:30:29.570 --> 00:30:33.160
And we say, OK, now that
you have seen it, now

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:37.600
that you have seen the water
in this new way, which water

00:30:37.600 --> 00:30:39.720
do you want your
children to drink?

00:30:39.720 --> 00:30:42.530
And if you can frame that
question in that way,

00:30:42.530 --> 00:30:44.180
people will change.

00:30:44.180 --> 00:30:46.550
People will give up a
little something else

00:30:46.550 --> 00:30:49.180
in order to have the safe
water for their families.

00:30:49.180 --> 00:30:53.100
And so to do that with
diet and exercise,

00:30:53.100 --> 00:30:55.990
to do that with
planning for retirement

00:30:55.990 --> 00:31:01.110
or saving for college or the
thousand other things, energy

00:31:01.110 --> 00:31:03.750
usage, or recycling,
or other things,

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:07.607
that's a big thing
to crack the code on.

00:31:07.607 --> 00:31:08.690
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: Right.

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:09.190
Thank you.

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:11.830
