00:35:29.940 --> 00:35:31.900
Fifth graders we worked with.

00:35:31.900 --> 00:35:32.520
Don't know.

00:35:32.520 --> 00:35:36.780
But that prompts a story,
which is one of the favorites.

00:35:36.780 --> 00:35:38.390
Of the 100 people
we interviewed,

00:35:38.390 --> 00:35:41.420
there's this teacher,
teaches the fifth grade.

00:35:41.420 --> 00:35:42.750
Her name is Marcy Barton.

00:35:42.750 --> 00:35:47.920
And she has been
teaching for 42 years.

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:51.680
And so I'm sure you've had those
kind of teachers, 42 years in.

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:54.560
They developed their
syllabus 41 years ago.

00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:57.180
And they've been in full
implementation/repetition mode

00:35:57.180 --> 00:35:57.810
ever since.

00:35:57.810 --> 00:36:00.110
And that doesn't
quite describe Marcy.

00:36:00.110 --> 00:36:03.980
So Marcy comes to the d.school.

00:36:03.980 --> 00:36:08.030
She comes to a two-day
program for educators.

00:36:08.030 --> 00:36:09.661
And by the way, I
am going to sound

00:36:09.661 --> 00:36:11.410
like a paid spokesperson
for the d.school.

00:36:11.410 --> 00:36:12.660
I'm not a Stanford guy at all.

00:36:12.660 --> 00:36:15.120
I'm a Berkeley guy, right?

00:36:15.120 --> 00:36:17.340
But Marcy is an amazing person.

00:36:17.340 --> 00:36:20.120
She comes to the d.school
for this two-day program.

00:36:20.120 --> 00:36:25.010
And based on that two days,
she basically changes her life.

00:36:25.010 --> 00:36:29.450
She reinvents her
curriculum from scratch

00:36:29.450 --> 00:36:32.200
after that two-day seminar.

00:36:32.200 --> 00:36:36.180
And she does all project-based
learning with her kids now.

00:36:36.180 --> 00:36:38.400
And so instead of
standing at the board

00:36:38.400 --> 00:36:41.810
and talking about
immigration in the New World,

00:36:41.810 --> 00:36:45.150
she turns the desks upside
down and puts the kids inside

00:36:45.150 --> 00:36:46.560
and wraps it with craft paper.

00:36:46.560 --> 00:36:47.580
And now they're in
they're in the ship going

00:36:47.580 --> 00:36:48.550
go into the New World.

00:36:48.550 --> 00:36:50.050
And they write
their constitution

00:36:50.050 --> 00:36:51.200
while they're in the ship.

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:53.575
And then, when they get there,
they use their math skills

00:36:53.575 --> 00:36:55.850
and make a perfect scale
model of the community.

00:36:55.850 --> 00:36:57.980
And everything is a project.

00:36:57.980 --> 00:37:02.440
And her kids have
done remarkably well.

00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:05.510
And Marcy, at one
point in the interview,

00:37:05.510 --> 00:37:08.590
she says, my kids are
wonderfully more creative

00:37:08.590 --> 00:37:09.560
and they're engaged.

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:12.922
And she says, and
write this down.

00:37:12.922 --> 00:37:15.130
And I'm thinking, Marcy,
we're taping this interview.

00:37:15.130 --> 00:37:17.190
But anyhow, she still
wants us to write.

00:37:17.190 --> 00:37:19.270
And she says, and
tell those parents,

00:37:19.270 --> 00:37:21.832
my kids do better on the
standardized tests, too.

00:37:21.832 --> 00:37:23.290
She says, of course,
they do better

00:37:23.290 --> 00:37:24.373
on the standardized tests.

00:37:24.373 --> 00:37:27.150
She says, my kids are
engaged every single day

00:37:27.150 --> 00:37:29.100
of the school year.

00:37:29.100 --> 00:37:31.860
And so Marcy says,
in the interview,

00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:34.710
this design thinking stuff
she picked up at the d.school,

00:37:34.710 --> 00:37:36.700
she says, this is
the cornerstone

00:37:36.700 --> 00:37:39.400
of my career and my life.

00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:40.680
And so that's Marcy story.

00:37:40.680 --> 00:37:43.540
But it's so ridiculously
unbelievable

00:37:43.540 --> 00:37:47.640
that David and I had to take
three steps back and think, OK,

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:50.210
how are we going to
explain this to anybody?

00:37:50.210 --> 00:37:52.070
So here's our theory.

00:37:52.070 --> 00:37:54.760
There's an old saying, sometimes
attributed to Plutarch,

00:37:54.760 --> 00:37:56.760
but there's another
possible source for it,

00:37:56.760 --> 00:38:00.490
where someone once said
that education is not

00:38:00.490 --> 00:38:02.240
the filling of a vessel,
it's the lighting

00:38:02.240 --> 00:38:06.030
of a fire, which is
not entirely true.

00:38:06.030 --> 00:38:08.480
Because in the
airline magazine, when

00:38:08.480 --> 00:38:12.980
it says you can learn Mandarin
in five days, that is bull.

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:15.075
You cannot learn
Mandarin in five days.

00:38:15.075 --> 00:38:15.700
And here's why.

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:17.590
Because it's the
filling of a vessel.

00:38:17.590 --> 00:38:18.889
It's vocabulary.

00:38:18.889 --> 00:38:19.430
It's grammar.

00:38:19.430 --> 00:38:20.200
It's tonality.

00:38:20.200 --> 00:38:22.690
It's really, really hard.

00:38:22.690 --> 00:38:26.780
But with Marcy, at the d.school,
she didn't fill any vessels.

00:38:26.780 --> 00:38:28.180
She lit a fire.

00:38:28.180 --> 00:38:31.380
She had almost everything
she needed and just

00:38:31.380 --> 00:38:34.910
had this one more spark
that set it all off.

00:38:34.910 --> 00:38:39.040
And so, anyhow, my favorite
fifth grade teacher

00:38:39.040 --> 00:38:44.370
in the world now, even though
we met fairly recently.

00:38:44.370 --> 00:38:46.772
DAVID KELLEY: Yeah, I'll
talk to five-year-olds.

00:38:46.772 --> 00:38:48.980
Because he didn't know if
it was five or fifth grade,

00:38:48.980 --> 00:38:49.896
so he did fifth grade.

00:38:49.896 --> 00:38:51.160
I'll talk to five-year-olds.

00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:52.940
So one of the things
we really found out,

00:38:52.940 --> 00:38:56.570
that was really interesting,
is that teachers never

00:38:56.570 --> 00:38:58.400
have time to give
the same problem,

00:38:58.400 --> 00:39:00.220
even if they're
project-based learning,

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:02.595
they don't have time to give
the same problem over again.

00:39:02.595 --> 00:39:04.810
And It turns out that
there's so much learning

00:39:04.810 --> 00:39:07.520
in becoming expert in
doing the same project over

00:39:07.520 --> 00:39:08.800
and over again.

00:39:08.800 --> 00:39:10.440
So you give them the project.

00:39:10.440 --> 00:39:13.880
And then everybody in the class
comes up with their ideas.

00:39:13.880 --> 00:39:17.520
And then you've learned so
much, you become more expert.

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:19.859
Because you have your ideas,
and you've worked on it.

00:39:19.859 --> 00:39:22.150
And then, you have all of
the other ideas or something,

00:39:22.150 --> 00:39:23.192
and then you do it again.

00:39:23.192 --> 00:39:24.358
So we've been experimenting.

00:39:24.358 --> 00:39:26.640
We experimented with that,
where the same project is

00:39:26.640 --> 00:39:28.000
given three times.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:33.040
And so I'll just tell you my
favorite kindergarten class.

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:37.510
And the problem we give them
is redesigning your bedroom.

00:39:37.510 --> 00:39:39.150
Fairly vigorous, anyway.

00:39:39.150 --> 00:39:40.859
So everybody comes back.

00:39:40.859 --> 00:39:41.650
And they come back.

00:39:41.650 --> 00:39:43.150
And they've got
their little models.

00:39:43.150 --> 00:39:45.860
And they're made out of
pipe cleaners and pieces

00:39:45.860 --> 00:39:47.524
of cardboard and stuff.

00:39:47.524 --> 00:39:48.940
I want to make a
long story short.

00:39:48.940 --> 00:39:51.982
This one little
girl has the design.

00:39:51.982 --> 00:39:52.940
They said, what's this?

00:39:52.940 --> 00:39:54.231
And she says, well, here is it.

00:39:54.231 --> 00:39:56.470
So we had them do need
finding and all this stuff.

00:39:56.470 --> 00:39:57.270
And she'd gone out.

00:39:57.270 --> 00:40:02.160
And her bedroom had a
place for the family car

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:03.730
to pull next to her bed.

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:07.470
Because her need was, when
we come home late at night

00:40:07.470 --> 00:40:10.970
and I'm asleep, Dad has to carry
me all the way from the garage

00:40:10.970 --> 00:40:11.840
into the bed.

00:40:11.840 --> 00:40:14.007
So in her design,
the door to the car

00:40:14.007 --> 00:40:16.090
opens-- she had a little
thing-- and she rolls out

00:40:16.090 --> 00:40:18.180
right out of the car
into the bed, right?

00:40:18.180 --> 00:40:18.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:18.680 --> 00:40:21.130
DAVID KELLEY: Anyway, so then
we do another round, another

00:40:21.130 --> 00:40:21.630
around.

00:40:21.630 --> 00:40:24.200
And by the end,
every kid-- that's

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:26.430
the killer app, right--
every kid's thing

00:40:26.430 --> 00:40:30.640
has a place for the car to park
next to their particular bed.

00:40:30.640 --> 00:40:32.367
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:32.367 --> 00:40:33.450
FREDERIK G. PFERDT: Great.

00:40:33.450 --> 00:40:34.330
More questions?

00:40:34.330 --> 00:40:35.310
AUDIENCE: Was there
any difference

00:40:35.310 --> 00:40:37.601
when you did the survey across
the different countries,

00:40:37.601 --> 00:40:39.230
or that survey
you had mentioned,

00:40:39.230 --> 00:40:43.465
in terms of culturally whether
the US or any one country

00:40:43.465 --> 00:40:45.590
is really behind or
really ahead and what

00:40:45.590 --> 00:40:46.080
the driver may have been?

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:46.788
TOM KELLEY: Sure.

00:40:46.788 --> 00:40:48.640
You gotta look at
the whole survey.

00:40:48.640 --> 00:40:50.620
I was interested in
the overall response.

00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:52.870
But when you look at the
individual country responses,

00:40:52.870 --> 00:40:53.870
it's fascinating.

00:40:53.870 --> 00:40:56.190
Because, basically,
every country

00:40:56.190 --> 00:40:58.700
thinks that they are the most
creative country in the world,

00:40:58.700 --> 00:41:00.980
right, though no one
else thinks they are.

00:41:00.980 --> 00:41:03.210
But the exception
to that is Japan.

00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:05.670
Everybody thinks that
Japan is creative

00:41:05.670 --> 00:41:07.510
except Japanese people.

00:41:07.510 --> 00:41:11.920
And so there's just this weird
kind of asymmetry to the belief

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:15.650
systems from country to country.

00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:18.201
But that gets at this very
central theme in our book,

00:41:18.201 --> 00:41:19.700
which is that
creative confidence is

00:41:19.700 --> 00:41:23.400
the combination of
the natural ability

00:41:23.400 --> 00:41:25.780
to come up with breakthrough
ideas and the courage

00:41:25.780 --> 00:41:27.370
to act on them.

00:41:27.370 --> 00:41:29.820
And so I've spent a ton
of my life in Japan.

00:41:29.820 --> 00:41:32.860
I think it's a tremendously
creative country.

00:41:32.860 --> 00:41:37.600
And sometimes, in
modern Japan, people

00:41:37.600 --> 00:41:39.540
don't have the courage
to stand up and say,

00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:40.990
this is a good idea.

00:41:40.990 --> 00:41:43.080
They feel like they
have to self-edit,

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:45.200
they can't express
their creativity.

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:46.980
And so, I think, a
huge opportunity there.

00:41:46.980 --> 00:41:48.710
But, yeah, country
by country, it's

00:41:48.710 --> 00:41:50.370
quite interesting
to see how they

00:41:50.370 --> 00:41:53.940
see themselves so differently
than other countries see them.

00:41:53.940 --> 00:41:58.300
DAVID KELLEY: And we do user
research all over the world

00:41:58.300 --> 00:41:58.800
constantly.

00:41:58.800 --> 00:42:04.740
And I mean, people
are completely

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:07.880
different in their desires.

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:08.950
So I remember.

00:42:08.950 --> 00:42:10.730
a vacuum cleaner
company asked us

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:13.030
to design a world
vacuum cleaner,

00:42:13.030 --> 00:42:15.839
like one vacuum cleaner that
they could sell everywhere

00:42:15.839 --> 00:42:16.380
in the world.

00:42:16.380 --> 00:42:21.450
And it was hilarious, because
you go around and talk

00:42:21.450 --> 00:42:22.950
to people about
vacuum cleaners, you

00:42:22.950 --> 00:42:25.440
realize just how different
the cultures are.

00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:27.447
You know, there
are places in Asia

00:42:27.447 --> 00:42:29.780
where they wanted a really
technical vacuum cleaner that

00:42:29.780 --> 00:42:33.540
counted dust mites and was
quiet and small and stuff.

00:42:33.540 --> 00:42:37.370
And people in the United States
want some big piece of metal

00:42:37.370 --> 00:42:39.700
that makes a loud
sucking noise, right?

00:42:39.700 --> 00:42:43.230
And so it was not possible to
do a world product, at least

00:42:43.230 --> 00:42:44.420
in this, physical things.

00:42:44.420 --> 00:42:48.035
You guys have a
better chance of that.

00:42:48.035 --> 00:42:51.000
AUDIENCE: Have you
guys had any instances

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:54.500
where the design approach
didn't work or it failed?

00:42:54.500 --> 00:42:56.842
And then, what did
you guys do about it?

00:42:56.842 --> 00:42:57.550
TOM KELLEY: Sure.

00:42:57.550 --> 00:42:58.425
Have we had failures?

00:42:58.425 --> 00:43:00.380
Yeah, you bet we have.

00:43:00.380 --> 00:43:02.350
I mean, this is the
essence of our approach.

00:43:02.350 --> 00:43:04.460
If you're not
failing, wow, you're

00:43:04.460 --> 00:43:05.770
just not taking any risks.

00:43:05.770 --> 00:43:07.210
It's like, I want
to learn to ski,

00:43:07.210 --> 00:43:09.500
but I never want to
fall down, right?

00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:11.030
Good luck with that.

00:43:11.030 --> 00:43:13.810
And so lots of
failures along the way.

00:43:13.810 --> 00:43:16.590
We were just doing a social
innovation project in Ghana

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:19.480
that had to do with,
let's just call it,

00:43:19.480 --> 00:43:22.530
sanitation issues so as not
to turn off the whole crowd.

00:43:22.530 --> 00:43:25.820
But anyhow, the sanitation issue
is public sanitation issues.

00:43:25.820 --> 00:43:29.030
And we had this idea
that we'd put up signs

00:43:29.030 --> 00:43:32.830
all over the
community and that we

00:43:32.830 --> 00:43:36.220
would draw maps of where the
big issues were by having people

00:43:36.220 --> 00:43:39.680
call in and say, over there,
there's a problem, over there.

00:43:39.680 --> 00:43:44.330
And so we put these signs up
all over the community, call in.

00:43:44.330 --> 00:43:47.460
And we got zero phone calls.

00:43:47.460 --> 00:43:50.140
I mean, well, in
fact, the phone rang.

00:43:50.140 --> 00:43:51.740
But nobody was ever there.

00:43:51.740 --> 00:43:53.190
It's like, what the heck?

00:43:53.190 --> 00:43:57.080
I mean, how are we going to
get data this way, right?

00:43:57.080 --> 00:43:59.440
And then, we were outsiders.

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:01.150
We didn't fully understand.

00:44:01.150 --> 00:44:04.100
We hadn't done all of
the design research

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:07.150
we needed to understand the
community we were working in.

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:08.850
And it turns out--
I guess, this is

00:44:08.850 --> 00:44:12.280
true in many parts of
Africa-- an incoming phone

00:44:12.280 --> 00:44:14.970
call on your cellphone is free.

00:44:14.970 --> 00:44:18.430
An outgoing phone call is
the one you pay for, right?

00:44:18.430 --> 00:44:21.940
So nobody is going to
pay for a phone call

00:44:21.940 --> 00:44:24.320
to tell you about
sanitation issues.

00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:26.920
And so there is this
practice very common

00:44:26.920 --> 00:44:29.390
in that part of the
world called flashing.

00:44:29.390 --> 00:44:32.220
And flashing is when you
call someone just enough

00:44:32.220 --> 00:44:35.840
to make their phone ring and
record your caller ID number,

00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:36.770
and then you hang up.

00:44:36.770 --> 00:44:38.820
And if they want to talk
to you-- in other words,

00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:41.246
if they want to pay
for the phone call--

00:44:41.246 --> 00:44:42.370
then they'll call you back.

00:44:42.370 --> 00:44:45.050
And so we went and changed all
of the signs all over and said,

00:44:45.050 --> 00:44:47.140
don't call this number,
flash this number.

00:44:47.140 --> 00:44:49.100
And then, we got all
kinds of data, right?

00:44:49.100 --> 00:44:51.174
But shame on us for not
having figured it out.

00:44:51.174 --> 00:44:53.090
I mean, we could have
printed those signs once

00:44:53.090 --> 00:44:54.660
instead of twice.

00:44:54.660 --> 00:45:00.170
But we were naive just as that
outsider in the Indian village

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:03.010
didn't fully understand
all of the things that

00:45:03.010 --> 00:45:05.700
were making those
family decisions.

00:45:05.700 --> 00:45:07.767
We didn't understand
the local community

00:45:07.767 --> 00:45:09.350
enough to get it
right the first time.

00:45:09.350 --> 00:45:11.349
DAVID KELLEY: Let me go
on record as saying IDEO

00:45:11.349 --> 00:45:13.420
doesn't fail at
the end very often.

00:45:13.420 --> 00:45:15.260
In the beginning,
it's a technique.

00:45:15.260 --> 00:45:15.860
At the end, we tend to--

00:45:15.860 --> 00:45:17.984
TOM KELLEY: Well, there
was that whole phase called

00:45:17.984 --> 00:45:20.520
pen-based computers, many of
you too young to remember.

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:23.456
But we and all of our
clients failed in that phase.

00:45:23.456 --> 00:45:24.580
Nobody wanted those things.

00:45:24.580 --> 00:45:27.140
DAVID KELLEY: Well, one
of my favorite discussions

00:45:27.140 --> 00:45:30.730
about failure is about one of
my buddies named John Cassidy.

00:45:30.730 --> 00:45:32.679
John Cassidy is a wonderful guy.

00:45:32.679 --> 00:45:33.970
He teaches at the d.school now.

00:45:33.970 --> 00:45:36.330
But he started a company
called Klutz Press.

00:45:36.330 --> 00:45:39.850
You know, Klutz Press is books
that you see in toy stores

00:45:39.850 --> 00:45:40.760
with stuff.

00:45:40.760 --> 00:45:43.530
Well, his first
project was called

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:46.180
"Juggling for the
Complete Klutz."

00:45:46.180 --> 00:45:48.012
And it's a long story.

00:45:48.012 --> 00:45:49.970
And he thought he was in
the juggling business.

00:45:49.970 --> 00:45:52.040
And he never came out with
a book for five more years.

00:45:52.040 --> 00:45:53.530
But then he figured he
was in the book business,

00:45:53.530 --> 00:45:54.830
and he's done very well.

00:45:54.830 --> 00:45:57.850
But he was in the juggling
business when he started.

00:45:57.850 --> 00:46:01.520
Anyway, I got this book.

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:03.310
I didn't know Cass at the time.

00:46:03.310 --> 00:46:05.769
But seemed like a good
idea, you know, juggling.

00:46:05.769 --> 00:46:07.810
I could impress the girls
at parties or something

00:46:07.810 --> 00:46:09.740
if I could juggle.

00:46:09.740 --> 00:46:12.680
And so I want to do that.

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:19.340
Well, the whole first half
of the book is about failing,

00:46:19.340 --> 00:46:23.830
about dropping the
ball on the floor.

00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:24.900
It's called the drop.

00:46:24.900 --> 00:46:27.577
He does nothing in this
book but desensitize you

00:46:27.577 --> 00:46:28.993
to the ball dropping
on the floor.

00:46:28.993 --> 00:46:30.284
He has lots of ways to do that.

00:46:30.284 --> 00:46:34.510
But the ball hitting the
floor is just not a big deal.

00:46:34.510 --> 00:46:37.900
It's not something that your
brain is trying to prevent,

00:46:37.900 --> 00:46:39.770
because it's so normal.

00:46:39.770 --> 00:46:41.990
And so, then, when
that happens, it's

00:46:41.990 --> 00:46:44.240
incredibly easy to
learn how to juggle,

00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:47.550
because it's just not that
mechanically difficult.

00:46:47.550 --> 00:46:49.100
But what's happening
is your brain's

00:46:49.100 --> 00:46:52.250
constantly worried about
or trying to keep you

00:46:52.250 --> 00:46:54.100
from dropping the
ball on the ground.

00:46:54.100 --> 00:46:57.400
And so it's a great example
of how you can get over

00:46:57.400 --> 00:47:00.754
that kind of fear that
you might make a mistake.

00:47:00.754 --> 00:47:02.170
And then you can
accomplish things

00:47:02.170 --> 00:47:03.970
that seem particularly
difficult.

00:47:03.970 --> 00:47:07.050
TOM KELLEY: You know, a great
microculture in the world that

00:47:07.050 --> 00:47:10.800
has got the right attitude about
failure is the gaming culture.

00:47:10.800 --> 00:47:13.240
I mean, you think about
gaming, it's about failure.

00:47:13.240 --> 00:47:15.450
I tell a story in the
book about my son Sean

00:47:15.450 --> 00:47:19.470
who, Christmas Day a few
years back, got the Tony Hawk

00:47:19.470 --> 00:47:21.015
skateboarding game.

00:47:21.015 --> 00:47:22.890
And those of you who
have played it may know,

00:47:22.890 --> 00:47:24.500
it's got a skateboard inside.

00:47:24.500 --> 00:47:26.660
It's got a full-size
skateboard that you stand on.

00:47:26.660 --> 00:47:29.830
And it controls the game.

00:47:29.830 --> 00:47:33.230
And he's there in front of three
generations of Kelleys, right,

00:47:33.230 --> 00:47:34.570
trying out his new game.

00:47:34.570 --> 00:47:38.160
And on-screen, his avatar-- you
know, his character on-screen,

00:47:38.160 --> 00:47:41.280
is smashing into the wall,
like, a couple of hundred times.

00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:43.740
And unlike some
other video games,

00:47:43.740 --> 00:47:47.230
he's also physically falling
off of the skateboard

00:47:47.230 --> 00:47:51.270
and nearly breaking
the glass coffee table

00:47:51.270 --> 00:47:52.530
and stuff like that.

00:47:52.530 --> 00:47:55.260
And I'm sitting there watching
him for, like, half an hour.

00:47:55.260 --> 00:47:58.430
And it suddenly occurs to
me, this is amazing, right?

00:47:58.430 --> 00:48:03.030
I mean, he's got the whole
family watching him fail time

00:48:03.030 --> 00:48:04.740
after time after
time, and he's not

00:48:04.740 --> 00:48:06.650
the tiniest bit embarrassed.

00:48:06.650 --> 00:48:09.420
So how is it that in
the gaming culture,

00:48:09.420 --> 00:48:11.230
you have this what
Jane McGonigal calls

00:48:11.230 --> 00:48:12.270
urgent optimism.

00:48:12.270 --> 00:48:13.600
It's like, OK, that failed.

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:15.749
Better try again, as
opposed to, in real life,

00:48:15.749 --> 00:48:17.040
where you say, oh, that failed.

00:48:17.040 --> 00:48:18.760
I'm marked for life, right?

00:48:18.760 --> 00:48:20.760
And so, if we can
have a little bit more

00:48:20.760 --> 00:48:23.260
of the gaming culture, the best
parts of the gaming culture,

00:48:23.260 --> 00:48:27.630
out here in the physical world,
that would be a good thing.

